  "body": "3500 What do *args and **kwargs mean in these function definitions? def foo(x, y, *args): pass def bar(x, y, **kwargs): pass See What do ** (double star/asterisk) and * (star/asterisk) mean in a function call? for the complementary question about arguments. python syntax parameter-passing variadic-functions argument-unpacking Share Improve this question Follow edited Feb 27, 2023 at 7:29 Karl Knechtel 61.7k 14 14 gold badges 136 136 silver badges 195 195 bronze badges asked Aug 31, 2008 at 15:04 Todd 36.4k 4 4 gold badges 25 25 silver badges 13 13 bronze badges 6 15 see also stackoverflow.com/questions/6967632/… Aaron Hall – Aaron Hall ♦ 2018-03-01 20:53:51 +00:00 Commented Mar 1, 2018 at 20:53 177 This question is a very popular duplicate target, but unfortunately it's often used incorrectly. Keep in mind that this question asks about defining functions with varargs ( def func(*args) ). For a question asking what it means in function calls ( func(*[1,2]) ) see here . For a question asking how to unpack argument lists see here . For a question asking what the * means in literals ( [*[1, 2]] ) see here . Aran-Fey – Aran-Fey 2019-03-22 20:40:26 +00:00 Commented Mar 22, 2019 at 20:40 6 @Aran-Fey: I think a better target for \"what does it mean in function calls\" is What does the star operator mean, in a function call? . Your link doesn't really address the use of ** , and it a much narrower question. ShadowRanger – ShadowRanger 2020-12-10 05:55:26 +00:00 Commented Dec 10, 2020 at 5:55 2 This question is - like many very old questions - sort of backwards; usually a question should be about how to solve a problem in new code, rather than how to understand existing code. For the latter, if you are closing something else as a duplicate, consider stackoverflow.com/questions/1993727/… (although this only covers * and not ** ). Karl Knechtel – Karl Knechtel 2022-04-17 04:51:36 +00:00 Commented Apr 17, 2022 at 4:51 1 stackoverflow.com/questions/3394835/use-of-args-and-kwargs was also closed as a duplicate of this, but you might find it better than this one. Karl Knechtel – Karl Knechtel 2022-06-21 03:31:18 +00:00 Commented Jun 21, 2022 at 3:31 | Show 1 more comment",
